<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Home on Arvind Iyer</title><link>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/</link><description>Recent content in Home on Arvind Iyer</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en</language><atom:link href="https://www.arvindkiyer.com/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Research</title><link>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/research/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/research/</guid><description>&lt;!-- My current research connects two related questions: which genomic alterations are selected during cancer evolution, and how epigenetic and regulatory cell states are selected and reorganized as tumors evolve and respond to treatment. --&gt;
&lt;h2 id="current--recent-works"&gt;Current &amp;amp; Recent Works&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;h3 id="epigenetic-determinants-of-cancer-cell-fate"&gt;Epigenetic determinants of cancer cell fate&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;div class="w3-row"&gt;
 &lt;div class="w3-col m4 l3 w3-center" style="padding-right: 20px;"&gt;
 &lt;img src="https://www.arvindkiyer.com/images/tnbc_cell_fate.png" alt="TNBC" class="w3-image " style="max-width: 100%; margin: 0 auto;"&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="w3-col m8 l9"&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is current, ongoing work in the &lt;a href="https://lupienlab.uhnresearch.ca/"&gt;Lupien Lab&lt;/a&gt; at Princess Margaret Cancer Centre, UHN, focused on triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) using single-cell RNA and ATAC (multiome) data. Central questions include:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Projects &amp; Software</title><link>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/projects/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/projects/</guid><description>&lt;div class="project-cards"&gt;

 &lt;div class="project-card w3-row" style="margin-bottom:2em;"&gt;
 
 &lt;div class="w3-col m4 l3 w3-center" style="padding-right:20px;"&gt;
 &lt;img src="https://www.arvindkiyer.com/images/select_sim.png" alt="SelectSim logo" class="w3-image" style="max-width:100%; margin:0 auto;"&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="w3-col m8 l9"&gt;
 
 &lt;h5&gt;SelectSim&lt;/h5&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;A statistical framework for detecting co-mutational patterns among genomic alterations in cancer.&lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Problem:&lt;/strong&gt; Identifying which combinations of genomic alterations are selected together during cancer evolution, beyond what is expected by chance.&lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;My contribution:&lt;/strong&gt; Contributed to development and application of the method, extending prior work on evolutionary dependencies (Mina et al.).&lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Status:&lt;/strong&gt; Published, actively maintained&lt;/p&gt;
 
 &lt;p&gt;
 &lt;a href="https://github.com/CSOgroup/SelectSim" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;GitHub&lt;/a&gt;
 · &lt;a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41588-020-0703-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener"&gt;Publication&lt;/a&gt;
 
 &lt;/p&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;

 &lt;div class="project-card w3-row" style="margin-bottom:2em;"&gt;
 
 &lt;div class="w3-col m4 l3 w3-center" style="padding-right:20px;"&gt;
 &lt;img src="https://www.arvindkiyer.com/images/cell_search.png" alt="CellAtlasSearch logo" class="w3-image" style="max-width:100%; margin:0 auto;"&gt;
 &lt;/div&gt;
 &lt;div class="w3-col m8 l9"&gt;
 
 &lt;h5&gt;CellAtlasSearch&lt;/h5&gt;
 &lt;p&gt;A scalable search engine for single-cell and bulk expression profiles, using GPU-accelerated Locality-Sensitive Hashing (LSH) for fast similarity search across large reference atlases.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Publications</title><link>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/publication/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://www.arvindkiyer.com/publication/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;For a complete and up-to-date list, see my &lt;a href="https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=0q8O0ecAAAAJ"&gt;Google Scholar profile&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
